Man, whenever Wharton puts Meme Financial Markets into its MBA core curricu=
lum and hires me to teach it, this is going to be the final exam:GameStop C=
orp. shares surged as speculation swirled around a return to social media b=
y Keith Gill, who drove the meme-stock mania of 2021 under the moniker =E2=
=80=9CRoaring Kitty.=E2=80=9DThe account=E2=80=99s post on X showed a man l=
eaning forward with what looked like a gaming controller, which some trader=
s interpreted to mean that Gill is coming back into action. Gill, whose acc=
ount has long been dormant, shot to fame in 2021 by rallying day traders on=
 Reddit in an effort to squeeze GameStop short sellers.The post had attract=
ed more than 12 million views in the hours since its publication.=C2=A0Gill=
 posted on X again at 11 a.m. New York time, this time a short video clip s=
tating =E2=80=9CFine, I=E2=80=99ll do it myself.=E2=80=9DThe reaction to Gi=
ll=E2=80=99s post shows shades of the original 2021 mania, with chatter acr=
oss Reddit=E2=80=99s WallStreetBets and activity on StockTwits sparking a r=
ush of retail trader buying.=E2=80=9CThat he is able to generate a crowd sa=
ys that the crowd is back to feeling FOMO and YOLO in an enormous way,=E2=
=80=9D said Peter Atwater, president of Financial Insyghts and an adjunct p=
rofessor at William & Mary and the University of Delaware. =E2=80=9CWhen pe=
ople dive into things that are of pure speculative value, their confidence =
is extremely high and this is one of the ways that it manifests.=E2=80=9DHe=
re is the first tweet, which does not make any fundamental or technical cas=
e=C2=A0for buying GameStop=E2=80=99s stock, or make any other arguments for=
 the stock, or mention GameStop, or contain any words at all. Just a drawin=
g of the guy leaning forward. There are some ambiguous=C2=A0follow-up video=
 clips. Prior to this, Gill had not tweeted since June 2021, and his YouTub=
e channel=C2=A0has been similarly dormant. GameStop=E2=80=99s=C2=A0stock op=
ened this morning at $26.34, up 51% from Friday=E2=80=99s close; it got as =
high as $38.20 at 10:05 a.m.,=C2=A0and was halted for volatility nine times=
 in the first two hours of trading.=C2=A0Some=C2=A0exam questions:=09What d=
o you think=C2=A0this tweet means?=C2=A0Is it about Gill=E2=80=99s return t=
o YouTube? To active stock trading? To GameStop? To some other stock? Is he=
 getting into computer gaming=C2=A0content? Taking a=C2=A0life drawing clas=
s and tweeting his work?=C2=A0=09Let=E2=80=99s say that you assign a=C2=A0p=
robability of X to =E2=80=9Cthis tweet means that Gill is going to be back =
on YouTube talking about GameStop a lot=E2=80=9D: How much does that change=
 your GameStop price target? Build an Excel model.=09What probability would=
 you assign to =E2=80=9Che=E2=80=99s gonna be on YouTube talking about Game=
Stop a lot, but now he=E2=80=99s short=E2=80=9D? How funny would that be?=
=09Is GameStop in a better or worse economic position than it was in Januar=
y 2021, when Gill first sent it to the moon? Is the range of possible outco=
mes now wider or narrower?=C2=A0Has the pivot to online commerce paid off? =
Is the pivot to letting Chief Executive Officer Ryan Cohen=C2=A0trade stock=
s with GameStop=E2=80=99s money going to pay off? The pivot to trading Pok=
=C3=A9mons? Do you care about any of this at all? Is it=C2=A0rational=C2=A0=
to care about any of it? If you have a strongly held=C2=A0view of the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s fundamentals, what should you do about it?=C2=A0=09How much mo=
ney=C2=A0has Citadel Securities made today because of this tweet?=C2=A0=09T=
he article goes on to quote Vanda Research=E2=80=99s Giacomo Pierantoni say=
ing: =E2=80=9CThese surges in retail activity have served as contrarian sig=
nals, prompting institutional investors to quickly short the stock followin=
g these rallies driven by retail investors.=E2=80=9D Shorting GameStop? Rea=
lly? Have the short sellers improved their timing since 2021, so that now t=
hey can short the stock=C2=A0following=C2=A0the rallies, rather than shorti=
ng early in the rallies and getting smoked? Or are the retail investors no =
longer as zealous and coordinated about punishing short sellers? Or=C2=A0we=
re=C2=A0they not as zealous and coordinated about punishing short sellers, =
but now Roaring Kitty is back to lead them into battle?=09Consider this hyp=
othetical=C2=A0trade: (1)=C2=A0Keith Gill buys a bunch of short-dated GameS=
top call options, (2) he tweets a picture of a guy leaning forward in a cha=
ir, (3) the stock shoots up, (4) he sells the options for a profit, (5) he =
never returns to YouTube or otherwise says anything about GameStop at all. =
Is this a good trade? How many times could he do this? If you bought GameSt=
op on the basis of his tweet, and this turned out to be the trade, how mad =
would you be?=09If you bought GameStop on the basis of his tweet, and he tu=
rned out to be just tweeting from his drawing class, how mad would you be?=
=09In the hypothetical trade in Question 7, would the US Securities and Exc=
hange Commission have a case against him for market manipulation?
  [1]
 In your answer, make reference to (1) the fact that the tweet doesn=E2=80=
=99t mention GameStop at all, (2) the recent decision by a federal judge in=
 Texas that actually pump and dumps are legal and (3) the 2023 decision by =
a federal judge in Washington, DC, that the moon emoji is securities fraud.=
=09Keith Gill seems to have added like $3 billion of market capitalization =
to GameStop by tweeting a picture of a guy. I assume he captured at=C2=A0mo=
st=C2=A0a tiny fraction of this value. Given this very particular skill tha=
t he has =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ability to add billions of dollars of value to,=
 at least, this=C2=A0stock, with essentially no effort =E2=80=94=C2=A0what =
is the best way for him to monetize it? What is the highest-value use that =
financial markets could find for=C2=A0Keith Gill?=09If you were Ryan Cohen,=
 would you hire Gill to run GameStop=E2=80=99s investor relations? If you w=
ere, like, Tesla, would you hire Gill to run investor relations? Trump Medi=
a & Technology Group? Apple? How much would you pay him?=09If you were Keit=
h Gill, would you go activist and try to take over GameStop? AMC Entertainm=
ent Holdings Inc.? Trump Media? Tesla? Apple?=C2=A0=09If you were Keith Gil=
l, would you set up a hedge fund with a strategy like =E2=80=9CI will oppor=
tunistically buy GameStop stock and then tweet to make it go up=E2=80=9D? W=
hat percentage of your gains would you charge as a performance fee? How muc=
h money could you raise? From whom? How much could you deploy?=C2=A0(In you=
r answer, consider Section 16=C2=A0and GameStop=E2=80=99s market capitaliza=
tion.) Would you add capacity by tweeting about other companies? Which ones=
? Would your investors go for that?=C2=A0If you were invited to speak at So=
hn, would you wear a bandana and pitch GameStop? Would you go out to dinner=
 afterwards with Gabe Plotkin?=09If you ran a multistrategy hedge fund, wou=
ld you hire Keith Gill to run a pod with a strategy like =E2=80=9Ctweet abo=
ut GameStop and make it go up=E2=80=9D? What kind of guarantee would you gi=
ve him? How much capital would you allocate to him? How often would you wan=
t him to run this trade? Would he have to be factor-neutral? What would he =
do the rest of the time? Would you bring him to investor-relations=C2=A0mee=
tings with limited partners?=09Is this just how life is now? In January 202=
1, the whole GameStop experience was new, and there was perhaps some genuin=
e uncertainty about how things would turn out. (Could GameStop keep going u=
p forever? Would there be the mother of all short squeezes? Could retail op=
tions buying create a perpetual motion machine?) And then the stock mostly =
fell back to earth, and the meme-stock machine ran again on other stocks wi=
th mostly diminishing results, and you could=C2=A0imagine=C2=A0that the who=
le thing was a confluence of novelty and social media and=C2=A0pandemic-era=
 boredom and incautious short sellers that would not repeat itself. But in =
fact is this just a permanent feature of financial markets?=C2=A0Here is Wh=
arton=E2=80=99s list of MBA finance classes, and there=E2=80=99s not even a=
n elective on meme stocks. There is FNCE7390, though, Behavioral Finance: =
=E2=80=9CThere is an abundance of evidence suggesting that the standard eco=
nomic paradigm =E2=80=94=C2=A0rational agents in an efficient market =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0does not adequately describe behavior in financial markets.=E2=80=
=9D Yes.
