   =20
      RIP Jim Simons
   =20
 =20
James Simons, arguably the greatest of all hedge fund managers,=C2=A0died l=
ast week. Every obituary of Simons mentions the key facts of his career, wh=
ich are that he knew (1) a lot about math and (2) nothing about finance.
  [2]
=C2=A0This seems to have been a very fruitful combination. If you can progr=
am computers to analyze data with, as it were, an open mind, they will pick=
 out signals from the data that work, and then you can trade on those signa=
ls and make an enormous fortune. If you insist on the signals making sense =
to you, you will just get in the way. Gregory Zuckerman writes:Early on, Si=
mons traded like most others, reading the news and betting on gold prices a=
nd other investments. He scored gains but found it hard to endure the marke=
t=E2=80=99s volatility. He developed stomach pains and berated himself for =
miscues.=E2=80=9COne day you=E2=80=99re a genius, the next you feel like a =
dope,=E2=80=9D Simons said. =E2=80=9CFundamental trading gave me ulcers.=E2=
=80=9DSimons set out to build an automated trading system that could discov=
er fleeting and overlooked patterns in prices.=E2=80=9CI want models that w=
ill make money while I sleep,=E2=80=9D Simons told a friend at the time. =
=E2=80=9CA pure system without humans interfering.=E2=80=9DSo he made them,=
 or hired people to. In 2010, Sebastian Mallaby summarized the approach of =
Simons=E2=80=99s then-deputies Peter Brown and Robert Mercer
  [3]
:It=E2=80=99s clear that the way Brown and Mercer approached programming wa=
s fundamentally different from the way other hedge-fund programmers thought=
 about it. At Tudor, for example, Sushil Wadhwani trained a machine to appr=
oach markets in a way that made sense for human traders. By contrast, Brown=
 and Mercer trained themselves to approach problems in a manner that made s=
ense for computers. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Presented with apparently random data an=
d no further clues, they sift it repeatedly for patterns, exploiting the po=
wer of computers to hunt for ghosts that to the human eye would be invisibl=
e. =E2=80=A6Robert Mercer =E2=80=A6 [says]: =E2=80=9CIf somebody came up wi=
th a theory about how the phases of Venus influence markets, we would want =
a lot of evidence.=E2=80=9D But he adds that =E2=80=9Csome signals that mak=
e no intuitive sense do indeed work.=E2=80=9D Indeed, it is the nonintuitiv=
e signals that often prove the most lucrative for Renaissance. =E2=80=9CThe=
 signals that we have been trading without interruption for fifteen years m=
ake no sense,=E2=80=9D Mercer explains. =E2=80=9COtherwise someone else wou=
ld have found them.=E2=80=9DArguably the point of these two sections is tha=
t=C2=A0if your view of financial markets makes too much sense then it is pr=
obably wrong.
 =20
   =20
      UBS
   =20
 =20
The thing about investment bankers is that they spend all day talking to ri=
ch people about money =E2=80=94 meeting with corporate chief executive offi=
cers and private equity investors to discuss mergers and financing =E2=80=
=94 but they would be hideously embarrassed to conclude those meetings by s=
aying =E2=80=9Coh and what about you, do you have enough life insurance, co=
uld we help you plan for retirement?=E2=80=9D The business of providing inv=
estment banking advice is totally separate from=C2=A0the business of provid=
ing personal financial advice. Even though the investment banker=E2=80=99s =
company also probably has a huge department that provides personal financia=
l advice and wealth management for rich people. And makes a lot of reliable=
 recurring revenue doing it. And is looking to expand it.And so every big i=
nvestment bank will from time to time announce an initiative that is like =
=E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re going to tell our investment bankers that they shoul=
d really mention our wealth management business to their corporate-executiv=
e clients,=E2=80=9D and it really does tell the investment bankers that, an=
d the investment bankers are like =E2=80=9Cyes we are team players and want=
 to help our wealth management colleagues bring in more revenue,=E2=80=9D b=
ut they shudder a little as they say it, and do they actually go out and pi=
tch the wealth management business? I don=E2=80=99t know, I=E2=80=99m not i=
n the meetings.One obvious problem with this approach is that the wealth ma=
nagers get paid for doing wealth management business, and the investment ba=
nkers get paid for doing investment banking business, and you can tell them=
 to cross-sell because they are all team players, but are they? Whereas if =
you just give them a referral fee:UBS Group AG is considering introducing a=
 reward system for investment bankers who refer clients to the firm=E2=80=
=99s wealth management business, according to people with knowledge of the =
matter.Some bankers would likely be in line for payouts in Asia and Europe =
when they successfully attract new money to the lender=E2=80=99s private ba=
nking unit, said the people, who asked not to be identified discussing conf=
idential plans. The referral fees would be a first for the Zurich-based len=
der, echoing earlier incentives that Credit Suisse had offered to its dealm=
akers, the people said.Part of me is like =E2=80=9Cyes obviously.=E2=80=9D =
Part of me is like =E2=80=9Cno, being a team player is priceless, and givin=
g people explicit bonuses for referrals cheapens it and makes people more m=
ercenary and less cooperative.=E2=80=9D But probably they are mercenary any=
way and you might as well try the bonuses.
 =20
   =20
      Outsider trading
   =20
 =20
If you work in a finance role at a public company, and you have early acces=
s to its earnings information, and you=E2=80=99ve got an annoying friend wh=
o sometimes texts you to be like =E2=80=9Chey how=E2=80=99s your company do=
ing,=E2=80=9D how should you respond? This is, I want to be clear, extra su=
per not legal advice, but I feel like a reasonable response might be =E2=80=
=9Cwe are doing very well, thanks for asking, but=C2=A0if you are asking be=
cause you plan to trade our stock, please do not do that.=E2=80=9D The esse=
ntial elements of this response are:=09You do not give your friend any insi=
de information. You do not give any details about performance, positive or =
negative.=09Oh, you do give a generic sunny statement that things are going=
 =E2=80=9Cvery well.=E2=80=9D You do this, to be clear, regardless of how t=
hings are going; if you know you are filing for bankruptcy tomorrow you sti=
ll tell this guy =E2=80=9Cdoing very well.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s none of hi=
s business! And =E2=80=9Cwe are doing very well=E2=80=9D conveys no informa=
tion =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s what any employee would generically say without=
 any inside information =E2=80=94 whereas =E2=80=9Cwe are not doing so grea=
t=E2=80=9D does carry a bearish signal. Even =E2=80=9Cwe are doing okay=E2=
=80=9D feels just a touch bearish, coming from a finance employee, no? =E2=
=80=9CVery well=E2=80=9D just seems like the neutral, information-free, pol=
itely loyal response.=09You tell your friend not to trade based on your con=
versations, because (1) if he trades and loses money, he will blame you, an=
d you are not trying to convey any information at all, and (2) if he trades=
 and makes money, after texting you, he=E2=80=99ll get arrested and you wil=
l be in trouble for conveying the information that you did not intend to co=
nvey.Again, I must emphasize that this is not legal advice, or even right a=
pparently, because here=E2=80=99s a pretty wild US Securities and Exchange =
Commission case:The Securities and Exchange Commission [Friday] charged Gib=
sonia, PA resident Frank T. Poerio, Jr. with insider trading for misappropr=
iating material, nonpublic information concerning Dick=E2=80=99s Sporting G=
oods Inc. and trading on that information, realizing illegal profits of mor=
e than $800,000.According to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, between November =
2019 and May 2021, Poerio knew a Dick=E2=80=99s employee who had access to =
multiple internal sources of material nonpublic information about the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s financial results. The SEC alleges that Poerio frequently aske=
d the employee for updates on the company=E2=80=99s performance, and, at ti=
mes, the employee responded with statements to the effect that the company =
was =E2=80=9Cdoing very well,=E2=80=9D coupled with requests that Poerio no=
t trade in Dick=E2=80=99s securities. The SEC alleges that Poerio understoo=
d that these statements were based on the employee=E2=80=99s access to nonp=
ublic financial information and previews of the company=E2=80=99s upcoming =
quarterly revenue figures. Poerio used this information to trade in Dick=E2=
=80=99s securities, in breach of his duty of trust and confidence to the em=
ployee.=E2=80=9CWe allege that Poerio exploited the trust of someone close =
to him by pumping that person for information and then ignoring his repeate=
d requests not to trade on that information,=E2=80=9D said Mark Cave, Assoc=
iate Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. =E2=80=9CToday=
=E2=80=99s charges showcase the SEC=E2=80=99s ability to detect and charge =
those who seek to profit off insider trading.=E2=80=9DHere is the complaint=
, which contains more details on the insider=E2=80=99s access to informatio=
n (including a real-time database with store-level sales information) and P=
oerio=E2=80=99s trading (he bought stock and call options, and sold put opt=
ions, around earnings releases, and made profits of $823,367), but no more =
details on their conversations. Just, like:During the time of Individual A=
=E2=80=99s employment with Dick=E2=80=99s Sporting Goods, Poerio frequently=
 asked Individual A for updates on the company=E2=80=99s performance, despi=
te knowing that insider trading was illegal. On some occasions, Individual =
A responded by telling Poerio that such information could not be disclosed.=
On other occasions, however, Individual A made statements to Poerio to the =
effect that the company was =E2=80=9Cdoing very well,=E2=80=9D and then rei=
terated requests that Poerio not trade in the securities of Dick=E2=80=99s =
Sporting Goods. Poerio understood that these statements about the company=
=E2=80=99s performance were based on Individual A=E2=80=99s access to nonpu=
blic revenue numbers, and that they provided a preview of the company=E2=80=
=99s upcoming quarterly financial reports.That is a lot to understand from =
the words =E2=80=9Cdoing very well=E2=80=9D! I think this is the worst insi=
der tip I=E2=80=99ve ever seen. To be fair, I am only reading=C2=A0the word=
s; there are ways to pronounce=C2=A0the words =E2=80=9Cdoing very well=E2=
=80=9D that mean =E2=80=9Cbuy as much as you can=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=
=80=9Cfine thanks for asking.=E2=80=9D Also, the SEC might be holding somet=
hing back. For instance, in advance of Dick=E2=80=99s November 2020 earning=
s, =E2=80=9CPoerio and Individual A spoke on the phone at least 122 times, =
a number which does not include texts or in-person meetings.=E2=80=9D Possi=
bly they got into more detail there than =E2=80=9Cdoing very well.=E2=80=9D
  [4]

