c;">obituary</a> of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/35362511.256340/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRzLWN1bHR1cmUvYm9va3MvamltL=
XNpbW9ucy1hLXBpb25lZXItb2YtcXVhbnRpdGF0aXZlLXRyYWRpbmctZGllcy02NjIxZDY2ZT9t=
b2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0411544d" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Simons</a> =
mentions the key facts of his career, which are that he knew (1) a lot abou=
t math and (2) nothing about finance.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#f=
ootnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0This seems to have been a very fruitful combination. If you can p=
rogram computers to analyze data with, as it were, an open mind, they will =
pick out signals from the data that work, and then you can trade on those s=
ignals and make an enormous fortune. If you insist on the signals making se=
nse <em>to you</em>, you will just get in the way. Gregory Zuckerman <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35362511.256340/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRzLWN1bHR1cmUvYm9va3MvamltLXNpbW9ucy1hLXBpb25lZXItb2Y=
tcXVhbnRpdGF0aXZlLXRyYWRpbmctZGllcy02NjIxZDY2ZT9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M3/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cC0411544d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">writes</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Early on, Simons traded like most others, reading the =
news and betting on gold prices and other investments. He scored gains but =
found it hard to endure the market=E2=80=99s volatility. He developed stoma=
ch pains and berated himself for miscues.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9COne day you=E2=80=99re a genius, the next you feel like a dope,=E2=
=80=9D Simons said. =E2=80=9CFundamental trading gave me ulcers.=E2=80=9D</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Simons set out to build an automated trading=
 system that could discover fleeting and overlooked patterns in prices.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI want models that will make money wh=
ile I sleep,=E2=80=9D Simons told a friend at the time. =E2=80=9CA pure sys=
tem without humans interfering.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">So he made them, or hired people to. In 2010, Sebastian Mallaby =
summarized the approach of Simons=E2=80=99s then-deputies Peter Brown and R=
obert Mercer<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s clear that t=
he way Brown and Mercer approached programming was fundamentally different =
from the way other hedge-fund programmers thought about it. At Tudor, for e=
xample, Sushil Wadhwani trained a machine to approach markets in a way that=
 made sense for human traders. By contrast, Brown and Mercer trained themse=
lves to approach problems in a manner that made sense for computers. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0Presented with apparently random data and no further clues, they s=
ift it repeatedly for patterns, exploiting the power of computers to hunt f=
or ghosts that to the human eye would be invisible. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robert Mercer =E2=80=A6 [says]: =E2=80=9CIf somebody c=
ame up with a theory about how the phases of Venus influence markets, we wo=
uld want a lot of evidence.=E2=80=9D But he adds that =E2=80=9Csome signals=
 that make no intuitive sense do indeed work.=E2=80=9D Indeed, it is the no=
nintuitive signals that often prove the most lucrative for Renaissance. =E2=
=80=9CThe signals that we have been trading without interruption for fiftee=
n years make no sense,=E2=80=9D Mercer explains. =E2=80=9COtherwise someone=
 else would have found them.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Arguably the point of these two sections is that=C2=A0if your view =
of financial markets makes too much sense then it is probably wrong.</p><ta=
ble class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadd=
ing=3D"0">
<tr>
