olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">just give them a referral fee</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">UBS Group AG is considering introducing a reward system for inv=
estment bankers who refer clients to the firm=E2=80=99s wealth management b=
usiness, according to people with knowledge of the matter.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Some bankers would likely be in line for payouts in Asia an=
d Europe when they successfully attract new money to the lender=E2=80=99s p=
rivate banking unit, said the people, who asked not to be identified discus=
sing confidential plans. The referral fees would be a first for the Zurich-=
based lender, echoing earlier incentives that Credit Suisse had offered to =
its dealmakers, the people said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Part of me is like =E2=80=9Cyes obviously.=E2=80=9D Part of me is like =
=E2=80=9Cno, being a team player is priceless, and giving people explicit b=
onuses for referrals cheapens it and makes people more mercenary and less c=
ooperative.=E2=80=9D But probably they are mercenary anyway and you might a=
s well try the bonuses.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D=
"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Outsider trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you work in a finance role at a pub=
lic company, and you have early access to its earnings information, and you=
=E2=80=99ve got an annoying friend who sometimes texts you to be like =E2=
=80=9Chey how=E2=80=99s your company doing,=E2=80=9D how should you respond=
? This is, I want to be clear, extra super not legal advice, but I feel lik=
e a reasonable response might be =E2=80=9Cwe are doing very well, thanks fo=
r asking, but=C2=A0if you are asking because you plan to trade our stock, p=
lease do not do that.=E2=80=9D The essential elements of this response are:=
</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px=
 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You do not give your friend any i=
nside information. You do not give any details about performance, positive =
or negative.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Oh, you <em>do</em> g=
ive a generic sunny statement that things are going =E2=80=9Cvery well.=E2=
=80=9D You do this, to be clear, <em>regardless </em>of how things are goin=
g; if you know you are filing for bankruptcy tomorrow you still tell this g=
uy =E2=80=9Cdoing very well.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s none of his business! An=
d =E2=80=9Cwe are doing very well=E2=80=9D conveys <em>no </em>information =
=E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s what any employee would generically say without any =
inside information =E2=80=94 whereas =E2=80=9Cwe are not doing so great=E2=
=80=9D <em>does </em>carry a bearish signal. Even =E2=80=9Cwe are doing oka=
y=E2=80=9D feels just a touch bearish, coming from a finance employee, no? =
=E2=80=9CVery well=E2=80=9D just seems like the neutral, information-free, =
politely loyal response.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You tell =
your friend not to trade based on your conversations, because (1) if he tra=
des and loses money, he will blame you, and you are not trying to convey an=
y information at all, and (2) if he trades and <em>makes </em>money, after =
texting you, he=E2=80=99ll get arrested and you will be in trouble for conv=
eying the information that you did not intend to convey.</li></ol><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, I must emphasize that this is not legal advice,=
 or even right apparently, because here=E2=80=99s a pretty wild <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35362511.256340/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyNC01Mw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
a5edb8ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">US Securities and Exchange Commission case</a>:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission [=
Friday] charged Gibsonia, PA resident Frank T. Poerio, Jr. with insider tra=
ding for misappropriating material, nonpublic information concerning Dick=
=E2=80=99s Sporting Goods Inc. and trading on that information, realizing i=
llegal profits of more than $800,000.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Accor=
ding to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, between November 2019 and May 2021, Po=
erio knew a Dick=E2=80=99s employee who had access to multiple internal sou=
rces of material nonpublic information about the company=E2=80=99s financia=
l results. The SEC alleges that Poerio frequently asked the employee for up=
dates on the company=E2=80=99s performance, and, at times, the employee res=
ponded with statements to the effect that the company was =E2=80=9Cdoing ve=
ry well,=E2=80=9D coupled with requests that Poerio not trade in Dick=E2=80=
=99s securities. The SEC alleges that Poerio understood that these statemen=
ts were based on the employee=E2=80=99s access to nonpublic financial infor=
mation and previews of the company=E2=80=99s upcoming quarterly revenue fig=
ures. Poerio used this information to trade in Dick=E2=80=99s securities, i=
n breach of his duty of trust and confidence to the employee.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe allege that Poerio exploited the trust of =
someone close to him by pumping that person for information and then ignori=
ng his repeated requests not to trade on that information,=E2=80=9D said Ma=
rk Cave, Associate Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. =
=E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=99s charges showcase the SEC=E2=80=99s ability to dete=
ct and charge those who seek to profit off insider trading.=E2=80=9D</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
